<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW LEGISLATION TO DEAL WITH HATE CRIMES IN UNITED STATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Roche would have us believe that racism and ethnic and religious bigotry have 
long since vanished from American society, evidenced by the fact that members 
of various groups are represented among the wealthy and that "even the chairman 
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff is black." Is Roche thereby suggesting that as a 
result of the presence of blacks in high appointed offices and the acquisition 
of material success by some minorities that crimes should no longer concern us? 
</P>
<P>
Roche misinterprets the impetus for the Hate Crimes Statistics Act. Crimes 
impelled by bias have a special emotional and psychological impact on the 
victim and the victim's community. They can lead to the intimidation of others 
in that community, causing them to feel isolated and unprotected by the law. 
The damage done by bias crimes cannot be measured solely in terms of physical 
injuries or by dollars. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, prejudice and hatred cannot be legislated or prosecuted out of 
existence, but at the very least, the enactment of this kind of legislation 
will demonstrate to the community that law enforcement officials have a genuine 
interest in the problem of bias crimes and a stake in vigorously pursuing the 
offenders. 
</P>
<P>
BETSY R. ROSENTHAL 
</P>
<P>
Western States Counsel 
</P>
<P>
Anti-Defamation League 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042690-0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 209522 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
April 26, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 6; Column 3; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
350 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORK FOR PRISONERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to David Glidden's column "Put Inmates to Work, Make Prison 
Produce," Opinion, April 1: 
</P>
<P>
Obviously, Glidden has no contact with prisons or their inmates. Prison slave 
labor is alive and well, it is called UNICOR, the Federal Prison Industries. 
Prisoners are paid from 22 cents per hour to $1.10 per hour to produce goods 
for the military (in direct competition with "major corporations"), the 
judicial branch of government and prisons themselves. It is a 
multimillion-dollar industry. UNICOR makes military uniforms, sheets, curtains, 
furniture, cables used on aircraft carriers, safety glasses/goggles, business 
forms, etc. Part of the profits are used to fund the education programs at all 
federal prisons. 
</P>
<P>
I have a master's degree in education. I taught school for 10 years. When I was 
arrested, I was an executive assistant at a concert company. I have no prior 
arrests. I've never been in trouble. I am 42 years old, white, female. I teach 
the GED program to fellow inmates who are helping themselves to be more 
productive when they leave here. My crime -- I unwittingly carried 2 kilos of 
cocaine from Los Angeles to Seattle by air. My sentence -- 8 years, 1 month 
with no possibility of parole. We are not "caged animals." We don't live 
"passively like domestic pets." We work very hard. Before teaching GED, I 
worked in the prison kitchen cleaning dishes, floors and pots and pans. For 98 
hours of work, I was paid $10.78. Candy bars cost 55 cents and copies cost 15 
cents a piece. 
</P>
<P>
I am not "plotting" my next crime. I did not plot the last one. I have 
discovered many women like myself, who were working, trying to make ends met, 
but ended up supplementing their income. We are not waiting for our next 
opportunity "to prey on society." We want to go home and take care of our 
children. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps, if inmates had been given decent-paying jobs, they would have had the 
"byproduct of self-respect," and never been incarcerated. It costs $25,000 per 
year to keep me in prison; that is more money than I ever made teaching school. 
</P>
<P>
JACQUELINE HENDRICKS 
</P>
<P>
Dublin, Calif. 
</P>
</TEXT>
