<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: STUDY AUTHORIZED ON USE OF RIVERBEDS FOR 
HIGHWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Los Angeles County Transportation Commission Wednesday authorized a 
$100,000 study of the feasibility of allowing car pools, buses and trucks to 
travel the beds of the Los Angeles River and the Tujunga Wash in order to 
relieve congestion. 
</P>
<P>
The six-month study will consider a proposal by Assemblyman Richard Katz 
(D-Sepulveda) to use the riverbed as a highway during rush hours on days when 
there is no threat of flooding. 
</P>
<P>
The commission voted to oppose a bill by state Sen. Art Torres (D-Los Angeles) 
that would require the state to plan the river as a park and would ban the 
commission from studying it for transportation. 
</P>
<P>
Torres and some environmentalists contend the river should be a verdant park, 
but Katz and others see it as a roadway that could be used as a park on 
evenings and weekends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
