CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SAN DIEGO; 
</P>
<P>
SURGEONS REMOVE BISHOP'S TUMOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Roman Catholic Bishop Leo T. Maher, who drew widespread attention when he 
banned a pro-choice political candidate from receiving Communion last year, was 
in serious condition after surgery to remove a brain tumor. Maher, 74, was 
alert and able to talk soon after the 2 1/2-hour operation at Scripps Clinic. 
</P>
<P>
Doctors said they were optimistic he would recover, but expressed concern about 
the possible recurrence of the life-threatening tumor. Maher, who oversees the 
462,000-member diocese encompassing San Diego and Imperial counties, may be 
released from the hospital in four to seven days, a Scripps spokeswoman said. 
Dr. Thomas Waltz, who led the operating team, said doctors removed 75% to 80% 
of the tumor, which was about 3 inches in diameter. "It's a tumor that you 
really can't classify as either malignant or benign," Waltz said. "It doesn't 
spread to other parts of the body. But it can recur." 
</P>
