<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
SCHOOL CONVERSIONS, CLOSURES CONSIDERED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN PENNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ocean View School District officials disclosed this week that they might close 
three schools and convert several elementary campuses to middle schools by 
June. 
</P>
<P>
The district, where enrollment has plummeted in recent years, faces a budget 
deficit of between $1.3 million and $1.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
Although officials have not yet announced which schools are being eyed for 
closure, about 100 angry parents, chiefly representing Vista View School, urged 
the school board Tuesday night not to close that school. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the parents said they had heard rumors that Vista View topped the 
district's list of schools targeted for closure, so they sent fliers home with 
students urging parents to attend the board meeting. But board President 
Charles Osterlund said no schools have been selected for closure. 
</P>
<P>
Osterlund said studies indicated that the district would need to eliminate 
three of its 17 schools to bring its average enrollment in line with other 
county districts. Some Ocean View campuses now have 40% fewer students than the 
norm. 
</P>
<P>
A committee of school and district officials and parents is holding a public 
hearing on the issue May 7 at Ocean View High School, and it will present its 
final proposal to the board eight days later. Trustees are scheduled May 22 to 
vote on that plan. 
</P>
<P>
The parents at Tuesday's board meeting said they are determined to voice their 
opinions well before the trustees make a final decision. They defended Vista 
View, a K-8 school with a strong academic record. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not trying to attack the board. We just want you to know that this is a 
community that backs this school," Randy Vanderhook, whose two children attend 
Vista View, told board members. "We don't want to get caught with our shorts 
down and then, boom, something happens and our school gets closed down." 
</P>
<P>
Osterlund told the parents they had no grounds for believing Vista View may be 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
"Many schools, eight or nine, are being looked at," he said. "There are many 
different plans concerning schools being closed down for various reasons, but 
there is not one school singled out. I think you do all of us a disservice" by 
suggesting Vista View may be closed. JOHN PENNER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
