</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROLL CALL: THE HOUSE; 
</P>
<P>
PRICE-FIXING ISSUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By a vote of 235 to 157, the House sent to the Senate a bill to help plaintiffs 
win lawsuits against vertical price-fixing, which occurs when manufacturers 
seek to enforce a minimum product price. The bill (HR 1236) eases Supreme 
Court-set standards of evidence that make it easy for judges to dismiss such 
suits. It gives plaintiffs a better chance of advancing their case to a jury. 
</P>
<P>
The bill is backed by discounters such as Burlington Coat Factory and K mart 
and opposed by business groups such as the Chamber of Commerce and National 
Assn. of Manufacturers, according to floor debate. 
</P>
<P>
Supporter Dan Glickman (D-Kan.) urged colleagues to "vote for your constituents 
who can't afford to shop at full-price retailers." 
</P>
<P>
Opponent G. V. (Sonny) Montgomery (D-Miss.) said the bill's defeat would 
"preserve the freedom of manufacturers . . . to determine how their products 
are marketed and serviced." 
</P>
<P>
Members voting yes supported the bill. 
</P>
