<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Standards of Evidence 
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 192 to 204, the House rejected an amendment to HR 1236 (above) 
toughening the standards of evidence in vertical price-fixing cases. This 
retained the bill's objective of making it easier for plaintiffs to avoid 
dismissal by a judge, and gain a jury trial, of their suits accusing 
manufacturers and distributors of conspiring against them because of their low 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
Supporters said the amendment would protect manufacturers who cut off discount 
dealers for reasons other than pricing policies. Foes said anti-trust policy is 
best served when vertical price-fixing cases are decided by juries. 
</P>
<P>
Members voting yes wanted to make it easier for judges to dismiss vertical 
price-fixing cases for lack of evidence. 
</P>
